title = "Forging Dies: Design, Materials, and Maintenance"

content = """
Forging dies are the heart of any forging operation and represent a major capital investment at Ridgecrest Metalworks. Die quality directly determines part dimensional accuracy, surface finish, flash control, and the number of parts produced per die before reconditioning.

Impression dies for closed-die forging consist of upper and lower die blocks machined with matched cavities that shape the forging. The cavity design must account for metal flow, draft angles (typically 5–7 degrees on vertical surfaces to allow part release), fillet radii (to promote smooth metal flow and prevent stress concentrations in the die), and the flash land and gutter (a narrow gap around the cavity perimeter where excess metal escapes as flash, controlling forging pressure and ensuring complete cavity fill). Die design today uses computer simulation (finite element analysis) to predict metal flow, identify fold or lap defect locations, and optimize preform shapes.

Die materials must withstand cyclic thermal stress from hot metal contact, high compressive stress, abrasion from metal flow, and impact loads. Hot work tool steels are standard: H11 and H13 chromium-molybdenum steels are most common for steel forgings, offering good hot hardness, toughness, and thermal fatigue resistance. Larger dies may use 6F2 or 6G steels. Die blocks are heat-treated to 36–48 HRC for a balance of hardness and toughness. Nitriding or PVD coatings on critical cavity surfaces can extend die life.

Die maintenance follows a structured program at Ridgecrest. After a set number of forging cycles (based on part complexity and material), dies are pulled, cleaned, and inspected for heat checks (network of fine surface cracks from thermal fatigue), erosion, washout, and dimensional wear. Worn cavity dimensions are measured against original inspection records. Dies are reconditioned by re-machining or by weld repair (using die repair welding procedures with controlled preheat and interpass temperature) followed by reheat treatment. Sink EDM or hard milling is used to re-cut cavities after weld buildup.

Die storage requires coating with rust-preventive oil and storage in a temperature-controlled area. Dies must be properly identified with heat numbers, part numbers, and reconditioning history records.
"""

